    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Further explanation...\n\n``` python\n>>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n>>> plt.plot([1,4,3])\n[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x04FC3450>]\n>>> plt.show()\n```\n\nThis code block works as expected in Python interpreter.\nIn IPython 2 after executing `plt.plot()` we'd loose focus from IPython \"interepreter\", so we'd had to use mouse (or other means) to regain the focus of the IPython \"interpreter\" and continue to work where we stopped after loosing the focus.\nIn IPython 3 focus remains in IPython 3 \"interpreter\", but executing `plt.show()` opens the plot in background.\n\nUsing something like `%matplotlib` or `%pylab` solves the problem, but the point here is that IPython mangles the focus from the expected behavior.\n"
  },
